{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1883"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.25,0.62,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31310"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1883"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17136"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42418"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31310"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 26-year-old man presents with a discoloured nail (Image). These visible changes have been present for about one month. There is no associated pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subungual melanoma","Subungual haematoma","Paronychia","Candidal infection","Whitlow"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis an example of onychomycosis, a relatively common fungal infection affecting the nails. The usual cause is a dermatophyte. It\u0027s not possible to distinguish whether the onychomycosis is caused by dermatophyte or candida on clinical examination alone. Both can induce variable changes including onycholysis, subungual hyperkeratosis, discoloration of the nailplate and dystrophy. \u003Cstrong\u003ECandida infection\u003C/strong\u003E is becoming increasingly common, particularly in immunosuppressed individuals, those with diabetes or individuals on broad spectrum antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is not a \u003Cstrong\u003Eparonychia\u003C/strong\u003E (which can result from a Candidal infection) as, by definition, there is involvement of the skin folds at the base or side of the nail in acute or chronic paronychia. In this instance, part of the nail itself has been destroyed by the fungus - and the adjacent skin is unaffected. A \u003Cstrong\u003Esubungual haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would be painful and associated with discolouration under the nail. \u003Cstrong\u003ESubungual melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon, but should always be considered in patients presenting with pigmented nail problems. In this case, the lesion is not pigmented. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ewhitlow\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute painful infection of the finger, most commonly herpetic in origin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Trichophyton rubrum is now the commonest cause of onychomycosis in the general population."],"references":["Welsh O, Vera-Cabrera L, Welsh E. Onychomycosis. Clin Derm. 2010; 18:151-59.","Jayatilake JAMS, Tilakaratne WM, Panagoda GJ. Candidal onychomycosis: a mini-review. Mycopathologia 2009; 168: 165-73."]},"relationships":